## Commander 14 ESM/TypeScript ÔÇö Validated Pattern

Commander 14.0.3 natively supports async action handlers and ESM. No extra config needed.

**Recommended pattern for our CLI:**
```typescript
import { Command } from 'commander';

const program = new Command()
  .name('o365-audit')
  .description('Office 365 Security Audit Framework')
  .version('1.0.0');

program.command('audit')
  .description('Run security audit checks')
  .option('--output-dir <dir>', 'Output directory for reports', './output')
  .option('--categories <cats...>', 'Categories to audit')
  .action(async (options) => {
    // async handler works natively
  });

program.parse();
```

- No need for `@commander-js/extra-typings` ÔÇö built-in types are sufficient for our simple CLI
- Subcommand nesting works via `.command()` chaining
- `program.parse()` (no args) defaults to `process.argv`

## Graph SDK PageIterator ÔÇö Built-in Pagination

The SDK has a built-in `PageIterator` class ÔÇö no need for manual `nextLink` handling.

```typescript
import { Client, PageIterator, PageCollection } from '@microsoft/microsoft-graph-client';

async function getAllItems<T>(client: Client, endpoint: string): Promise<T[]> {
  const items: T[] = [];
  const response: PageCollection = await client.api(endpoint).get();

  const callback = (item: T) => {
    items.push(item);
    return true; // continue
  };

  const pageIterator = new PageIterator(client, response, callback);
  await pageIterator.iterate();
  return items;
}
```

**Key facts:**
- Import: `import { PageIterator } from '@microsoft/microsoft-graph-client'`
- Callback returns `true` to continue, `false` to pause
- `pageIterator.isComplete()` checks if all pages consumed
- Handles `@odata.nextLink` automatically
- Works with both v1.0 and beta endpoints

**Exception:** `directoryRoles` endpoint does NOT support `$top` (already noted in epic). Use PageIterator without `.top()` for that endpoint.

## Research Area 1 & 4: ESM Auto-Discovery with Node 24

**Finding: `node:fs/promises` has native `glob()` in Node 24** ÔÇö no external library needed.

```ts
import { glob } from "node:fs/promises";
import { pathToFileURL } from "node:url";

async function discoverChecks(checksDir: string) {
  const checks = [];
  for await (const file of glob("dist/checks/**/check-*.js")) {
    const url = pathToFileURL(path.resolve(file)).href;
    const mod = await import(url);
    if (mod.meta && mod.run) checks.push(mod);
  }
  return checks;
}
```

- Convention: check files named `check-*.ts` in category subdirs
- Dynamic `import()` works with `file://` URLs for ESM
- Glob pattern `dist/checks/**/check-*.js` discovers from compiled output
- No need for explicit registry ÔÇö auto-discovery is clean and native

## Research Area 2 & 3: Function-Based Plugin Pattern (Recommended over Class-Based)

**Recommendation: Switch from class-based `AuditCheck` to function-based exports.**

Each check file exports `meta` (CheckMeta) and `run` (function):

```ts
// types.ts ÔÇö refined
export type Severity = "critical" | "high" | "medium" | "low" | "info";
export type CheckStatus = "pass" | "fail" | "warn" | "error";

export interface FrameworkMapping {
  name: string;    // "CIS M365 v3.1", "NIST 800-53"
  control: string; // "1.1.1", "IA-2"
}

export interface CheckMeta {
  id: string;           // "identity-001"
  name: string;         // "MFA Enabled for All Users"
  category: string;     // "identity"
  severity: Severity;
  service: string;      // "Entra ID", "Exchange Online"
  frameworks: FrameworkMapping[];
}

export interface Finding {
  resource: string;     // "user:john@example.com"
  detail: string;
}

export interface CheckResult {
  status: CheckStatus;
  message: string;
  findings?: Finding[];
}

export interface CheckContext {
  graphClient: Client;
  config: AuditConfig;
}

// Each check file:
// export const meta: CheckMeta = { ... };
// export async function run(ctx: CheckContext): Promise<CheckResult> { ... }
```

**Why function-based over class-based:**
- Simpler ÔÇö no `new` instantiation, just import and call
- Better tree-shaking potential
- Easier to test (just call the function)
- Works naturally with dynamic `import()` auto-discovery

## Research Area 5: Aggregation Approach

**`Object.groupBy()` is native in Node 24** ÔÇö no lodash needed.

```ts
// Group results by severity
const bySeverity = Object.groupBy(results, r => r.meta.severity);

// Group by category
const byCategory = Object.groupBy(results, r => r.meta.category);

// Group by service
const byService = Object.groupBy(results, r => r.meta.service);

// Summary counts
const summary = {
  total: results.length,
  pass: results.filter(r => r.result.status === "pass").length,
  fail: results.filter(r => r.result.status === "fail").length,
  critical: results.filter(r => r.meta.severity === "critical" && r.result.status === "fail").length,
};
```

The runner should return an `AuditReport` that pairs each check's meta with its result:
```ts
export interface AuditReport {
  timestamp: Date;
  results: Array<{ meta: CheckMeta; result: CheckResult }>;
  summary: { total: number; pass: number; fail: number; warn: number; error: number };
}
```

